During the review of my [CL 744880](https://go.dev/cl/744880), @alexbrainman requested that I remove all helper methods on the newly added structs. Their interpretation of the [proposal process documentation](https://github.com/golang/proposal) is that adding these "fictitious" methods requires a formal proposal.

However, this differs from the feedback I received on my earlier [CL 695195](https://go.dev/cl/695195), where reviewers actually wanted me to add even more helper methods than I had initially included. This contradiction can hurt consistency throughout the `x/sys` repo. Maybe someone can clarify what exactly the policy is on this, and update the documentation?

For context, the new API in question looks like the following:

```go
func GetIfTable2Ex(level uint32, table **MibIfTable2) (errcode error)

type MibIfTable2 struct {
	NumEntries uint32
	Table      [1]MibIfRow2
}

func (t *MibIfTable2) Rows() []MibIfRow2 {
	return unsafe.Slice(&t.Table[0], t.NumEntries)
}
```

The memory pointed to by `table` is allocated and managed by Windows. `Rows` simply provides an idiomatic way to access the table by returning a slice to the contents of the table.

cc @ianlancetaylor, as @alexbrainman asked for your opinion in the review comments of [CL 744880](https://go.dev/cl/744880).

cc @qmuntal I'm curious about your opinion since you reviewed [CL 695195](https://go.dev/cl/695195).

### Proposal Details

--- Accepted proposal:
```go
// A History provides a (possibly bounded) queue of input lines read by [ReadLine].
type History interface {
	// Add adds a new, most recent entry to the history.
	// It is allowed to drop any entry, including
	// the entry being added (e.g.,, if it's a whitespace-only entry),
	// the least-recent entry (e.g., to keep the history bounded),
	// or any other entry.
	Add(entry string)

	// Len returns the number of entries in the history.
	Len() int

	// At returns an entry from the history.
	// Index 0 is the most-recently added entry and
	// index Len()-1 is the least-recently added entry.
	// If index is < 0 or >= Len(), it panics.
	At(index int) string
}

type Terminal struct {
        ...

        // History records and retrieves lines of input read by [ReadLine].
        //
        // It is not safe to call ReadLine concurrently with any methods on History.
        // 
        // [NewTerminal] sets this to an implementation that records the last 100 lines of input.
        History History
}
```

copied from https://github.com/golang/go/issues/68780#issuecomment-2810426043

--- Was "Interface" Proposal:

https://github.com/golang/term/pull/20/files

```go
// The History interface provides a way to replace the default automatic
// 100 slots ringbuffer implementation.
type History interface {
	// Add will be called by Terminal to add a new line into the history.
	// An implementation may decide to not add every lines by ignoring calls
	// to this function (from Terminal.ReadLine) and to only add validated
	// entries out of band.
	Add(entry string)

	// At retrieves a line from history.
	// idx 0 should be the most recent entry.
	// return false when out of range.
	At(idx int) (string, bool)
}

// In terminal:

	// History allows to replace the default implementation of the history
	// which contains previously entered commands so that they can be
	// accessed with the up and down keys.
	// It's not safe to call ReadLine and methods on History concurrently.
	History History
```
--- 
